ğŸŒ¡ï¸ DAILY TEMPERATURES

(Monotonic Stack â€“ VERY IMPORTANT for interviews)

ğŸ”¹ Problem Definition

You are given an array temperatures[] where
temperatures[i] = temperature on day i.

For each day, find how many days you have to wait until a warmer temperature.
If there is no future day with a warmer temperature, return 0 for that day.

ğŸ”¹ Example
Input
temperatures = [73,74,75,71,69,72,76,73]

Output
[1,1,4,2,1,1,0,0]

Explanation

Day 0 (73) â†’ warmer at day 1 â†’ wait 1 day

Day 2 (75) â†’ warmer at day 6 â†’ wait 4 days

Day 6 (76) â†’ no warmer day â†’ 0

âŒ Brute Force (Donâ€™t Use)

For each day, check all future days.

Time: O(nÂ²) âŒ

Interviewer will reject this

âœ… Optimal Approach: MONOTONIC STACK
ğŸ”‘ Core Idea (VERY IMPORTANT ğŸš¨)

Use a stack of indices

Stack stores days with decreasing temperatures

When a warmer temperature appears:

Pop index

Calculate difference in days

ğŸ”¹ Algorithm (Step-by-Step)

Create an answer array

Create an empty stack

Traverse temperatures from left to right

While stack is not empty and current temp > stack top temp:

Pop index

Answer = currentIndex âˆ’ poppedIndex

Push current index into stack

Remaining stack elements â†’ answer = 0

ğŸ”¹ Java Code (Interview Ready)
class Solution {
    public int[] dailyTemperatures(int[] temperatures) {

        int n = temperatures.length;
        int[] answer = new int[n];

        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

            while (!stack.isEmpty() &&
                   temperatures[i] > temperatures[stack.peek()]) {

                int prevDay = stack.pop();
                answer[prevDay] = i - prevDay;
            }

            stack.push(i);
        }

        return answer;
    }
}

ğŸ§  LINE-BY-LINE EXPLANATION
int[] answer = new int[n];


âœ” Stores number of days to wait for warmer temperature

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();


âœ” Stores indices, not values
âœ” Helps compute day difference

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)


âœ” Traverse each day

temperatures[i] > temperatures[stack.peek()]


âœ” Current day is warmer than previous day

int prevDay = stack.pop();
answer[prevDay] = i - prevDay;


âœ” Compute number of days waited

stack.push(i);


âœ” Push current day index for future comparison

ğŸ” Dry Run (Important for Interview)

Input:

[73,74,75,71,69,72,76,73]


Stack evolution:

Day 0 â†’ push
Day 1 â†’ pop 0 â†’ ans[0]=1
Day 2 â†’ pop 1 â†’ ans[1]=1
Day 3 â†’ push
Day 4 â†’ push
Day 5 â†’ pop 4 â†’ ans[4]=1
Day 6 â†’ pop 5,3,2 â†’ ans updated


Final Answer:

[1,1,4,2,1,1,0,0]

â± Time & Space Complexity
Type	Complexity
Time	O(n)
Space	O(n)
ğŸ¯ Interview One-Liner

â€œI use a monotonic decreasing stack to keep track of previous colder days. When a warmer temperature appears, I pop indices and calculate the waiting days.â€
